    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Color Palette Picker</h2>
      <p>
        Click or tap anywhere on the color palette above. The horizontal axis represents the full hue spectrum from red through orange, yellow, green, cyan, blue, violet, and back to red. The vertical axis varies brightness and saturation, with vivid colors near the top and softer, lighter tones toward the bottom. When you click, a crosshair marks your position and a side panel appears showing a large swatch of the exact color along with its HEX, RGB, and HSL codes. Click the "Copy" button next to any format to send it to your clipboard.
      </p>
      <p>
        The palette is rendered on an HTML canvas, which means every pixel is a distinct color. You can pick extremely precise shades by clicking carefully. If you need to type in an exact value instead, use the companion Color Converter tool, which lets you enter HEX, RGB, or HSL values directly and converts between all three formats.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Color Formats</h2>
      <p>
        The three formats displayed by this tool each serve a different purpose. HEX notation like <code>#3B82F6</code> is the most compact and widely used in CSS and HTML. It encodes the red, green, and blue components as two hexadecimal digits each. RGB notation like <code>rgb(59, 130, 246)</code> uses decimal values from 0 to 255 for each color channel, which is easier to read and modify programmatically. HSL notation like <code>hsl(217, 91%, 60%)</code> describes colors in terms of hue (the position on the color wheel), saturation (how vivid the color is), and lightness (how bright or dark it is), making it the most intuitive format for manual color adjustments.
      </p>

      <h3>Choosing Colors for Web Design</h3>
      <p>
        Good color choices are rarely random. Most professional designs use a primary color, a secondary color, a neutral palette (grays), and an accent color for interactive elements. The primary color should reinforce the brand identity and work well against both white and dark backgrounds. Use the palette to explore hues visually, then refine with the Color Converter for precise adjustments. When building a design system, define your colors as CSS custom properties using HSL, because you can create lighter and darker variants by adjusting only the lightness value.
      </p>

      <h3>Accessibility Considerations</h3>
      <p>
        Colors that look distinct on your monitor may not be distinguishable to users with color vision deficiency. Roughly eight percent of men and half a percent of women have some form of color blindness. Beyond color choice, ensure that text always meets WCAG contrast requirements: 4.5:1 for normal text and 3:1 for large text against its background. The companion Color Converter tool calculates contrast ratios automatically so you can verify accessibility before committing to a palette.
      </p>

      <h3>From Palette to Production</h3>
      <p>
        Once you pick a color, paste the HEX or HSL code directly into your CSS, Tailwind config, Figma color tokens, or design system documentation. HEX codes also work in SVG fill and stroke attributes, email HTML templates, and image editing tools. HSL is the best choice for Tailwind custom colors because you can define the hue and saturation once and generate an entire shade scale by varying lightness from 50 (lightest) to 950 (darkest).
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How does the picker work?</h3>
      <p>
        The palette is drawn on an HTML canvas covering the full color spectrum. When you click, the tool reads the exact pixel color at that position and converts it to HEX, RGB, and HSL formats.
      </p>

      <h3>What color formats are shown?</h3>
      <p>
        HEX (e.g., #3B82F6), RGB (e.g., rgb(59, 130, 246)), and HSL (e.g., hsl(217, 91%, 60%)). Each has a copy button. All three are CSS-ready.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I pick exact shades?</h3>
      <p>
        The palette covers the full spectrum with gradients for brightness and saturation. For exact values, use the Color Converter to type in specific codes.
      </p>

      <h3>Is this useful for web design?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. The codes copy directly into CSS, Tailwind configs, Figma, and design system tokens. HSL is especially useful for generating shade scales.
      </p>

      <h3>Does it work on mobile?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Tap anywhere on the palette to pick a color. The side panel with codes appears below the canvas on smaller screens.
      </p>

